@node Main "Appendix 3: Date Format Strings..."
@toc "FinalCalc:guide/main.guide/Main"
@font topaz.font 8
In FinalCalc, the way a date is shown is defined by the Date Format used to
display it.  The date format is a string made up of tokens that are used to
define how the date is displayed.


@{b}@{u}Date Format Tokens:@{ub}@{uu}

    d       One/Two digit day number.  If the number is a single digit, it is
            padded with a space to keep things aligned.
    dd      Two digit day number.  e.g.  21, 01
    ddd     Three digit day number, from the start of the year.  This is the
            day number of the year, ignoring months.  e.g. 10 Sep is 253. 
            This is useful for dates like 253.1991  (format "ddd.yyyy")

    m       One letter month name.
    mm      Two letter month name.
    mmm     Three letter month name... e.g. Jan, Feb, Mar, etc.
    mmmm    Full name of month.. e.g.  Janurary, February, March, etc.

    n       One/Two digit month number.
    nn      Two digit month number.

    yy      Two digit year number... e.g. 90, 91, 01, etc.
    yyyy    Four digit year number... e.g. 1990, 1991, 2001, etc.

    w       Day of the week, M, T, W, T, F, S, S
    ww      Day of the week, Mo, Tu, We, Th, Fr, Sa, Su
    www     Day of the week, Mon, Tue, Wed, Thu, Fri, Sat, Sun
    wwww    Day of the week, Monday, Tuesday, Wednesday, Thursday,
                             Friday, Saturday, Sunday

    \\       Any letter following the back-slash will not be interpreted, and
            will be copied to the output format string.


@{b}@{u}Capitalization in weekday and month name display formats:@{ub}@{uu}

    If the first letter in the format type is upper-case, the first letter in
    the output name is upper case.  If the second letter in the format type is
    upper-case, then the rest of the weekday/month name is output in upper case.

    w       m, t, w
    W       M, T, w
    ww      mo, tu, we
    Ww      Mo, Tu, We
    WW      MO, TU, WE
    www     mon, tue, wed
    Www     Mon, Tue, Wed
    WWW     MON, TUE, WED
    wwww    monday, tuesday, wednesday
    Wwww    Monday, Tuesday, Wednesday
    WWWW    MONDAY, TUESDAY, WEDNESDAY

    The same applies for month formats.


    Examples:
    
    dd Mmm yy           01 Feb 90
    dd/MMM/yy           01/FEB/90
    d/n/yyyy             1/ 2/1990
    Mmmm yy             February 90
    d mmm                1 feb
    Mmm d, yyyy         Feb  1, 1990
    \\Welco\\me Mmmm!     Welcome February!


@{b}@{u}Date Format String requester:@{ub}@{uu}

The Date Format String requester comes up when you click on a [?] gadget
attached to a string gadget that expects a date format string (e.g.
"dd Mmm yyyy").

The requester shows you a list of the tokens you can use and what each does.
It allows you to select and paste the tokens right into the string, while
showing you 'live' what the resulting date string will look like.
@endnode
